222.answer:
Binary search finds a target in a **sorted** array by repeatedly checking the middle element and discarding half the search space each step.

```js
function binarySearch(arr, target) {
  let left = 0;
  let right = arr.length - 1;

  while (left <= right) {
    const mid = Math.floor((left + right) / 2);

    if (arr[mid] === target) return mid;
    if (arr[mid] < target) left = mid + 1;
    else right = mid - 1;
  }

  return -1;
}
```

Example:
```js
binarySearch([1, 3, 5, 7, 9], 7); // 3
```

Time complexity: **O(log n)**. It only works correctly if the array is sorted.

