Markdown headings use `#` prefixes: `#` for level 1, `##` for level 2, up to `######` for level 6. The number of `#` characters indicates depth, so lower numbers are higher-level sections. A nested table of contents can be built by walking headings in order and attaching each heading to the nearest earlier heading with a smaller level.
```js
function parseMarkdownToc(markdown) {
  const lines = markdown.split(/\r?\n/);
  const roots = [];
  const stack = [];

  for (const line of lines) {
    const match = line.match(/^(#{1,6})\s+(.+?)\s*#*\s*$/);
    if (!match) continue;

    const level = match[1].length;
    const title = match[2].trim();
    const node = { title, level, children: [] };

    while (stack.length && stack[stack.length - 1].level >= level) {
      stack.pop();
    }

    if (stack.length === 0) {
      roots.push(node);
    } else {
      stack[stack.length - 1].children.push(node);
    }

    stack.push(node);
  }

  return roots;
}
```

Example:

```js
const md = `# Intro
## Install
## Usage
### CLI
# API
## Auth`;

console.log(JSON.stringify(parseMarkdownToc(md), null, 2));
```

Output shape:

```js
[
  {
    title: 'Intro',
    level: 1,
    children: [
      { title: 'Install', level: 2, children: [] },
      {
        title: 'Usage',
        level: 2,
        children: [
          { title: 'CLI', level: 3, children: [] }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    title: 'API',
    level: 1,
    children: [
      { title: 'Auth', level: 2, children: [] }
    ]
  }
]
```

