752.answer:
Merge sort is a divide-and-conquer algorithm:

- Split the array into two halves.
- Recursively sort each half.
- Merge the two sorted halves by repeatedly taking the smaller front element.

Why it works:
- Arrays of length 0 or 1 are already sorted.
- If both halves are sorted, the merge step produces one fully sorted array.

Complexity:
- **Time:** `O(n log n)` in the best, average, and worst case
- **Space:** `O(n)` extra space for merged arrays

JavaScript implementation:

```js
function mergeSort(arr) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) {
    return arr.slice();
  }

  const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
  const left = mergeSort(arr.slice(0, mid));
  const right = mergeSort(arr.slice(mid));

  return merge(left, right);
}

function merge(left, right) {
  const result = [];
  let i = 0;
  let j = 0;

  while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
    if (left[i] <= right[j]) {
      result.push(left[i]);
      i++;
    } else {
      result.push(right[j]);
      j++;
    }
  }

  while (i < left.length) {
    result.push(left[i]);
    i++;
  }

  while (j < right.length) {
    result.push(right[j]);
    j++;
  }

  return result;
}
```

Example:

```js
const numbers = [38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10];
console.log(mergeSort(numbers)); // [3, 9, 10, 27, 38, 43, 82]
```

This version returns a new sorted array and does not modify the original.

753.answer:
Quicksort sorts by choosing a **pivot**, partitioning the array so values `<= pivot` go left and values `> pivot` go right, then recursively sorting the two sides.

Why it’s useful:
- Average time: **O(n log n)**
- Worst case: **O(n²)** when pivots are poor
- Extra space: **O(log n)** from recursion for an in-place version

With the **last element as pivot**, the partition step scans the range and moves smaller elements forward, then places the pivot in its final sorted position.

```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class QuickSort {
    public static void quickSort(int[] arr) {
        if (arr == null || arr.length < 2) {
            return;
        }
        quickSort(arr, 0, arr.length - 1);
    }

    private static void quickSort(int[] arr, int low, int high) {
        if (low < high) {
            int pivotIndex = partition(arr, low, high);
            quickSort(arr, low, pivotIndex - 1);
            quickSort(arr, pivotIndex + 1, high);
        }
    }

    private static int partition(int[] arr, int low, int high) {
        int pivot = arr[high];
        int i = low - 1;

        for (int j = low; j < high; j++) {
            if (arr[j] <= pivot) {
                i++;
                swap(arr, i, j);
            }
        }

        swap(arr, i + 1, high);
        return i + 1;
    }

    private static void swap(int[] arr, int i, int j) {
        int temp = arr[i];
        arr[i] = arr[j];
        arr[j] = temp;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {10, 7, 8, 9, 1, 5};
        quickSort(arr);
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));
    }
}
```

For `{10, 7, 8, 9, 1, 5}`, output is:

```java
[1, 5, 7, 8, 9, 10]
```

