Union-find (disjoint set union, or DSU) tracks a collection of non-overlapping sets and supports two fast operations:

- `find(x)`: returns the representative/root of the set containing `x`
- `union(a, b)`: merges the sets containing `a` and `b`

It’s useful for connectivity problems, grouping, and Kruskal’s minimum spanning tree.

### Core idea
Each element points to a parent. A root is an element whose parent is itself. Every set is represented as a tree of parent pointers.

Example:
- If `1, 2, 3` are connected, they may all eventually point to root `1`
- `find(3)` follows parent links until it reaches `1`

### Optimizations
#### 1. Path compression
During `find(x)`, make every visited node point directly to the root.

That flattens the tree, making future operations much faster.

#### 2. Union by rank
When merging two trees, attach the shorter tree under the taller one.

`rank` is an upper bound on tree height. This keeps trees shallow.

Together, these make operations almost constant time in practice.

### JavaScript implementation
```js
class UnionFind {
  constructor(size) {
    this.parent = Array.from({ length: size }, (_, i) => i);
    this.rank = Array(size).fill(0);
    this.count = size;
  }

  find(x) {
    if (this.parent[x] !== x) {
      this.parent[x] = this.find(this.parent[x]);
    }
    return this.parent[x];
  }

  union(a, b) {
    let rootA = this.find(a);
    let rootB = this.find(b);

    if (rootA === rootB) {
      return false;
    }

    if (this.rank[rootA] < this.rank[rootB]) {
      this.parent[rootA] = rootB;
    } else if (this.rank[rootA] > this.rank[rootB]) {
      this.parent[rootB] = rootA;
    } else {
      this.parent[rootB] = rootA;
      this.rank[rootA] += 1;
    }

    this.count -= 1;
    return true;
  }

  connected(a, b) {
    return this.find(a) === this.find(b);
  }

  getSetCount() {
    return this.count;
  }
}
```

### Example usage
```js
const uf = new UnionFind(6);

uf.union(0, 1);
uf.union(1, 2);
uf.union(3, 4);

console.log(uf.connected(0, 2)); // true
console.log(uf.connected(0, 4)); // false
console.log(uf.getSetCount());   // 3

uf.union(2, 4);
console.log(uf.connected(0, 4)); // true
```

### Time complexity
With path compression + union by rank:
- `find`: amortized nearly O(1)
- `union`: amortized nearly O(1)

More precisely, both are `O(α(n))`, where `α` is the inverse Ackermann function, which grows so slowly it’s effectively constant for real inputs.

