776.answer:
A hash table stores key-value pairs by computing an array index from each key with a hash function. Average-case insert, lookup, and delete are usually **O(1)** if the hash function spreads keys well.

### Core idea
- **Hash function**: turns a key into an integer.
- **Buckets**: array slots where entries live.
- **Collision**: two keys map to the same bucket.
- **Separate chaining**: each bucket holds a list of entries, so collisions are handled by scanning that bucket’s list.

### Why it works
If keys are distributed evenly, each bucket stays short, so operations only inspect a small number of entries.

### Tradeoffs
- Very fast average-case operations.
- Performance degrades if many keys collide.
- Needs resizing when the table gets too full.

### Simple separate-chaining hash map in JavaScript
Supports:
- **string keys**
- **integer values**
- `set`, `get`, `has`, `delete`

```js
class HashMap {
  constructor(initialCapacity = 16) {
    this.buckets = Array.from({ length: initialCapacity }, () => []);
    this.size = 0;
  }

  _hash(key) {
    let hash = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < key.length; i++) {
      hash = (hash * 31 + key.charCodeAt(i)) >>> 0;
    }
    return hash % this.buckets.length;
  }

  _resize() {
    const oldBuckets = this.buckets;
    this.buckets = Array.from({ length: oldBuckets.length * 2 }, () => []);
    this.size = 0;

    for (const bucket of oldBuckets) {
      for (const [key, value] of bucket) {
        this.set(key, value);
      }
    }
  }

  set(key, value) {
    if (typeof key !== 'string') {
      throw new TypeError('Key must be a string');
    }
    if (!Number.isInteger(value)) {
      throw new TypeError('Value must be an integer');
    }

    if ((this.size + 1) / this.buckets.length > 0.75) {
      this._resize();
    }

    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (let i = 0; i < bucket.length; i++) {
      if (bucket[i][0] === key) {
        bucket[i][1] = value;
        return;
      }
    }

    bucket.push([key, value]);
    this.size++;
  }

  get(key) {
    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (const [k, v] of bucket) {
      if (k === key) {
        return v;
      }
    }

    return undefined;
  }

  has(key) {
    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (const [k] of bucket) {
      if (k === key) {
        return true;
      }
    }

    return false;
  }

  delete(key) {
    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (let i = 0; i < bucket.length; i++) {
      if (bucket[i][0] === key) {
        bucket.splice(i, 1);
        this.size--;
        return true;
      }
    }

    return false;
  }
}

// Example usage
const map = new HashMap();
map.set('apple', 3);
map.set('banana', 7);
map.set('apple', 10);

console.log(map.get('apple'));   // 10
console.log(map.get('banana'));  // 7
console.log(map.has('pear'));    // false
console.log(map.delete('banana')); // true
console.log(map.get('banana'));  // undefined
console.log(map.size);           // 1
```

### Complexity
- **set**: average **O(1)**
- **get**: average **O(1)**
- **delete**: average **O(1)**
- Worst case for all: **O(n)** if everything lands in one bucket

