The adapter pattern wraps an incompatible API and exposes the interface your app expects. It lets new code talk to old code without changing either side directly.

In your case, the app wants JSON, but the legacy service speaks XML. The adapter sits in between: it accepts JSON-shaped input/output at the boundary, converts requests to XML for the legacy service, then converts XML responses back to JSON.

```ts
// Target interface: what the modern app expects
interface UserService {
  getUser(id: string): Promise<{ id: string; name: string; email: string }>;
}

// Legacy service: incompatible XML-based API
class LegacyXmlUserService {
  async fetchUser(xmlRequest: string): Promise<string> {
    const id = xmlRequest.match(/<id>(.*?)<\/id>/)?.[1] ?? "unknown";

    // Simulated XML response from legacy system
    return `
      <user>
        <id>${id}</id>
        <name>Jane Doe</name>
        <email>jane@example.com</email>
      </user>
    `.trim();
  }
}

// Adapter: converts between JSON interface and XML service
class XmlToJsonUserServiceAdapter implements UserService {
  constructor(private readonly legacyService: LegacyXmlUserService) {}

  async getUser(id: string): Promise<{ id: string; name: string; email: string }> {
    const xmlRequest = this.toXml({ id });
    const xmlResponse = await this.legacyService.fetchUser(xmlRequest);
    return this.fromXml(xmlResponse);
  }

  private toXml(data: { id: string }): string {
    return `<request><id>${this.escapeXml(data.id)}</id></request>`;
  }

  private fromXml(xml: string): { id: string; name: string; email: string } {
    return {
      id: this.readTag(xml, "id"),
      name: this.readTag(xml, "name"),
      email: this.readTag(xml, "email"),
    };
  }

  private readTag(xml: string, tag: string): string {
    const match = xml.match(new RegExp(`<${tag}>(.*?)<\\/${tag}>`));
    if (!match) throw new Error(`Missing <${tag}> in XML response`);
    return match[1];
  }

  private escapeXml(value: string): string {
    return value
      .replace(/&/g, "&amp;")
      .replace(/</g, "&lt;")
      .replace(/>/g, "&gt;")
      .replace(/"/g, "&quot;")
      .replace(/'/g, "&apos;");
  }
}

// Client code uses only the JSON-based interface
async function main() {
  const legacyService = new LegacyXmlUserService();
  const userService: UserService = new XmlToJsonUserServiceAdapter(legacyService);

  const user = await userService.getUser("123");
  console.log(user);
  // { id: '123', name: 'Jane Doe', email: 'jane@example.com' }
}

main().catch(console.error);
```

### Why this is useful
- Keeps legacy code unchanged
- Keeps new code clean and JSON-focused
- Centralizes XML/JSON conversion in one place
- Makes later replacement of the legacy service easier

