The command pattern encapsulates a request as an object so you can parameterize actions, queue them, log them, and support undo without the caller knowing the action details.

Core roles:
- **Receiver**: the object that does the real work (`Light`)
- **Command**: an object with `execute()` and usually `undo()`
- **Invoker**: triggers commands (`RemoteControl`)
- **Client**: wires everything together

It’s useful when you want to decouple *what triggers an action* from *how the action is performed*.

```javascript
class Light {
  constructor(location = 'Light') {
    this.location = location;
    this.isOn = false;
  }

  on() {
    this.isOn = true;
    console.log(`${this.location} is ON`);
  }

  off() {
    this.isOn = false;
    console.log(`${this.location} is OFF`);
  }
}

class LightOnCommand {
  constructor(light) {
    this.light = light;
  }

  execute() {
    this.light.on();
  }

  undo() {
    this.light.off();
  }
}

class LightOffCommand {
  constructor(light) {
    this.light = light;
  }

  execute() {
    this.light.off();
  }

  undo() {
    this.light.on();
  }
}

class RemoteControl {
  constructor() {
    this.history = [];
  }

  submit(command) {
    command.execute();
    this.history.push(command);
  }

  undoLast() {
    const command = this.history.pop();

    if (!command) {
      console.log('Nothing to undo');
      return;
    }

    command.undo();
  }
}

// Client code
const livingRoomLight = new Light('Living room light');
const lightOn = new LightOnCommand(livingRoomLight);
const lightOff = new LightOffCommand(livingRoomLight);
const remote = new RemoteControl();

remote.submit(lightOn);   // Living room light is ON
remote.submit(lightOff);  // Living room light is OFF
remote.undoLast();        // Living room light is ON
remote.undoLast();        // Living room light is OFF
remote.undoLast();        // Nothing to undo
```

If you want, I can also show a version using a reusable `Command` base class or function-based commands.

