This is **open redirect**, not SSRF.

Why:
- **Open redirect** happens when server code sends the **user’s browser** to a URL influenced by user input.
- **SSRF** happens when the **server itself** makes a request to a user-controlled URL.

Your prompt says “allowing redirects only to `https://a` and `https://b`” (the end of the sentence appears truncated), which strongly suggests the vulnerable code is doing something like `redirect(req.query.next)` or equivalent.
- If the code only returns an HTTP 3xx with a `Location` header, that is **not SSRF**.
- It is **open redirect** if an attacker can supply an arbitrary external destination.
- It is **both** only if the server also fetches that URL itself.
- It is **neither** if the redirect target is fixed or strictly validated already.

A safe pattern is to parse the URL and allowlist exact origins.

```js
const ALLOWED_REDIRECT_ORIGINS = new Set([
  'https://a',
  'https://b',
]);

function getSafeRedirectTarget(input) {
  if (!input) return 'https://a';

  try {
    const url = new URL(input);

    if (ALLOWED_REDIRECT_ORIGINS.has(url.origin)) {
      return url.toString();
    }
  } catch {}

  return 'https://a';
}

app.get('/redirect', (req, res) => {
  const target = getSafeRedirectTarget(req.query.next);
  res.redirect(target);
});
```

Stricter version if you want to allow only those exact URLs and nothing under them:

```js
const ALLOWED_REDIRECT_URLS = new Set([
  'https://a/',
  'https://b/',
]);

function getSafeRedirectTarget(input) {
  try {
    const url = new URL(input);
    if (ALLOWED_REDIRECT_URLS.has(url.toString())) {
      return url.toString();
    }
  } catch {}

  return 'https://a/';
}
```

